      <div class="article-content" style="font-size: 14px; line-height: 1.8; color: #ccc;">

        <p>Polling rate — also called report rate — is how many times per second your mouse sends its position data to your computer. It is measured in Hertz (Hz). A mouse with a polling rate of 1000 Hz reports its position 1000 times per second, meaning every 1 millisecond. At 125 Hz, the mouse reports only 8 times per second — every 8 milliseconds. That 7ms difference may sound small, but in competitive gaming it is quite significant.</p>

        <h2>How Polling Rate Affects Input Latency</h2>
        <p>Every time you move your mouse, that movement data sits in a buffer until the next poll occurs. At 125 Hz, you might wait up to 8ms before your PC even receives the movement. At 1000 Hz, the maximum wait is 1ms. At 8000 Hz, it drops to just 0.125ms.</p>
        <p>This polling delay adds directly to your system's total input latency chain — which includes game engine processing time, render time, display response time, and monitor scan-out delay. Reducing poll rate delay is therefore one of the most hardware-accessible ways to reduce your total input-to-display lag.</p>

