        <h2>Does Poll Rate Matter for You? The Refresh Rate Relationship</h2>
        <p>Here is the key insight that most guides miss: your monitor's refresh rate is the practical ceiling for how useful a higher polling rate can be. At 60 Hz, a new frame is drawn every 16.7ms. If your mouse reports at 1000 Hz, 16 out of every 17 position reports are "wasted" in the sense that they arrive between frame renders. The game engine can only sample your latest position once per frame anyway.</p>
        <p>This doesn't mean 1000 Hz is useless at 60 Hz — the game engine still benefits from having the latest position data available when it renders — but it does mean the jump from 1000 Hz to 8000 Hz is far more meaningful at 360 Hz than at 60 Hz.</p>

        <div style="background:#111; border:1px solid #2a2a2a; border-left:3px solid #39ff14; padding:16px 20px; border-radius:6px; margin:24px 0;">
          <strong style="color:#39ff14; font-size:12px; text-transform:uppercase; letter-spacing:0.08em;">Rule of Thumb</strong>
          <p style="margin:8px 0 0; font-size:13px; color:#ccc;">Match your polling rate to your refresh rate. At 60–144 Hz, 500–1000 Hz polling is sufficient. At 240–360 Hz, 1000–4000 Hz is ideal. At 360 Hz+, 4000–8000 Hz becomes beneficial if your hardware supports it without CPU overhead issues.</p>
        </div>

        <h2>The CPU Overhead Problem at 4000 Hz and 8000 Hz</h2>
        <p>Ultra-high polling rates come with a hidden cost: they increase CPU interrupt frequency dramatically. At 8000 Hz, your mouse is interrupting the CPU 8000 times per second. On high-end CPUs this overhead is negligible, but on older or budget processors — or systems with many other USB devices — it can actually <em>reduce</em> gaming performance by stealing CPU time from the game engine.</p>
        <p>Several esports players and testers have reported that switching from 8000 Hz to 1000 Hz improved their FPS in CPU-limited games. Mice like the Razer DeathAdder V3 HyperSpeed and Logitech G Pro X Superlight 2 are designed to minimize this overhead, but it is still worth testing. If you notice FPS drops or stutters after enabling 8000 Hz, drop back to 4000 Hz or 1000 Hz.</p>

        <h2>How to Check and Change Your Mouse Polling Rate</h2>
        <p>Most gaming mice ship at 1000 Hz by default, but you can verify or change your polling rate using the manufacturer's software (Logitech G Hub, Razer Synapse, SteelSeries GG, etc.) or through the dedicated button/switch on some mice. To verify your actual polling rate in real time, use our <a href="/mouse-poll-rate" style="color:#39ff14; text-decoration:none;">Mouse Poll Rate Test</a> — it measures your mouse's reported position frequency directly in your browser.</p>

        <h2>Wired vs Wireless: Does It Affect Poll Rate?</h2>
        <p>Modern wireless gaming mice — particularly those using proprietary 2.4 GHz receivers (Logitech LIGHTSPEED, Razer HyperSpeed, SteelSeries Quantum Wireless) — achieve the same 1000 Hz polling as wired. Some flagship wireless mice like the Razer DeathAdder V3 HyperSpeed now support 4000 Hz wirelessly. The only wireless technology that has historically been limited in polling rate is Bluetooth, which typically caps at 125 Hz due to the protocol's design — avoid Bluetooth for competitive gaming.</p>

        <h2>Polling Rate vs. DPI: What Should You Prioritize?</h2>
        <p>DPI and polling rate are related but separate. DPI (Dots Per Inch) controls how many pixels your cursor moves per inch of physical mouse movement — it's a sensitivity multiplier. Polling rate controls how often that movement data is sent to the PC.</p>
        <p>For most gamers, the optimal upgrade path is: (1) ensure your mouse runs at 1000 Hz, (2) set your DPI to match your preferred sensitivity and monitor resolution, then (3) if you have a 240 Hz+ monitor and a high-end PC, consider upgrading to a 4000 Hz capable mouse. Going straight to 8000 Hz without the rest of your system being up to spec is largely wasted investment.</p>

        <h2>Which Polling Rate Should You Use?</h2>
        <ul style="padding-left:20px; margin-bottom:24px;">
          <li style="margin-bottom:8px;"><strong style="color:#e8e8e8;">Casual / office use:</strong> 125–500 Hz is perfectly fine</li>
          <li style="margin-bottom:8px;"><strong style="color:#e8e8e8;">60–144 Hz gaming:</strong> 1000 Hz is the sweet spot — no benefit from going higher</li>
          <li style="margin-bottom:8px;"><strong style="color:#e8e8e8;">240 Hz gaming:</strong> 1000–4000 Hz, depending on your CPU and mouse</li>
          <li style="margin-bottom:8px;"><strong style="color:#e8e8e8;">360 Hz+ gaming:</strong> 4000–8000 Hz if your system can handle the overhead</li>
          <li style="margin-bottom:8px;"><strong style="color:#e8e8e8;">CPU-limited system:</strong> Stick to 1000 Hz to avoid performance regressions</li>
        </ul>

